You can terminate a C program by using the exit() function. The exit() function takes an integer as an argument, which is the status code of the program. The status code is used by the operating system to determine the exit status of the program. The exit() function is typically used in the main() function of a program to terminate the program. For example, you can use the following code to terminate a program with a status code of 0:
```
#include <stdlib.h>

int main() {
    // Your program code here
    exit(0);
    return 0;
}
```
Alternatively, you can use the return statement to terminate a program. The return statement is used to return a value from a function, but it can also be used to terminate a program. For example, you can use the following code to terminate a program with a status code of 0:
```
#include <stdlib.h>

int main() {
    // Your program code here
    return 0;
}
```
You can also use the abort() function to terminate a program. The abort() function is used to terminate a program immediately, without giving it a chance to clean up. For example, you can use the following code to terminate a program:
```
#include <stdlib.h>

int main() {
    // Your program code here
    abort();
    return 0;
}
```
It is important to note that the exit() function should be used with caution, as it can cause unexpected behavior in some cases. The return statement is generally safer to use, as it allows the program to clean up before terminating.

